For an example of where we might emphasize one modeling agenda over another, consider the application of encoding machine-readable annotations of digital resources. In an address to a humanities computing symposium at King's College, John Unsworth listed annotation among seven scholarly primitives, i.e., "basic functions common to scholarly activity across disciplines, over time, and independent of theoretical orientation" (
). Supporting digital annotation has long been a core use case in the humanities, but the growing role of response and feedback in both online social media and digital commerce has encouraged the understanding of annotations as a resource genre in their own right. A variety of architectures have consequently been adopted or proposed as bases for digital annotation, including HyTime (
), the Multivalent Framework (
), the Linguistic Annotation Framework (
) and the Open Annotation Data Model (
).

